{"descriptions":[{"id":630,"title":"Exorcism","content":"\u003ch1\u003eDescription\u003c/h1\u003e \u003cp\u003eThis category overlaps with \"\u003ca href=\"../../../../../features/2380\"\u003eProtection rituals\u003c/a\u003e\" (\u003cem\u003ebsrung\u003c/em\u003e) and \"\u003ca href=\"../../../../../features/1908\"\u003eDestruction rituals\u003c/a\u003e\" (\u003cem\u003egrol, bsad\u003c/em\u003e), as the three form a common triad \u003cem\u003ebsrung bzlog bsad gsum\u003c/em\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e \u003cp\u003eProtection rituals usually anticipate the attack of opposing forces, providing a first line of defense before an attack takes place. Exorcisms, on the other hand, usually serve to turn back attacks that have already taken place. In extreme cases, enemies (humans or spirits) may be killed using destructive rituals.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e \u003cp\u003eThe \"Exorcism\" Knowledge Map category is also used for \"ransom\" rituals, which often use effegies to repurchase one's soul or life-force.\u003c/p\u003e \u003ch1\u003eRelated Terms\u003c/h1\u003e \u003cp\u003ebzlog bsgyur, bskrad thabs, 'grol ba, glud, dbang sdud, zhi bar byed pa, 'dul ba, gto, gto yas, gto 'bol\u003c/p\u003e \u003ch1\u003eExample Texts\u003c/h1\u003e \u003cul\u003e \u003cli\u003eSee also \u003ca href=\"http://tbrc.org/#!rid=T1726\"\u003ebzlog bsgyur\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/li\u003e \u003c/ul\u003e \u003ch1\u003eSecondary Sources\u003c/h1\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u003c!--[if gte mso 9]\u003e\u003cxml\u003e Normal 0 false false false MicrosoftInternetExplorer4 \u003c/xml\u003e\u003c![endif]--\u003e\u003c!--[if gte mso 9]\u003e\u003cxml\u003e \u003c/xml\u003e\u003c![endif]--\u003e\u003c!--[if !mso]\u003e \u003cspan class=\"mceItemObject\" classid=\"clsid:38481807-CA0E-42D2-BF39-B33AF135CC4D\" id=ieooui\u003e \u003c/span\u003e \u003cmce:style\u003e\u003c! st1\\:*{behavior:url(#ieooui) } --\u003e \u003c!--[endif]--\u003e\u003c!-- --\u003e\u003c!--[if gte mso 10]\u003e \u003cmce:style\u003e\u003c! /* Style De